<recipeml version="0.5">
  <recipe>
    <head>
      <title>American Farm Sausages - 13</title>
      <categories>
        <cat>Pork</cat>
        <cat>Sausage-mak</cat></categories>
      <yield>5</yield></head>
    <ingredients>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>5</qty>
          <unit>pounds</unit></amt>
        <item>Pork; grind medium</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1</qty>
          <unit>tablespoon</unit></amt>
        <item>Black pepper</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>5</qty>
          <unit>teaspoons</unit></amt>
        <item>Salt</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1</qty>
          <unit>tablespoon</unit></amt>
        <item>Sage</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1</qty>
          <unit>teaspoon</unit></amt>
        <item>Cayenne pepper</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1/2</qty>
          <unit>teaspoons</unit></amt>
        <item>Ginger</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1</qty>
          <unit/></amt>
        <item>Bay leaf; crushed</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1</qty>
          <unit>cup</unit></amt>
        <item>Cold water</item></ing></ingredients>
    <directions>
      <step>  It had a lot of recipes for country-style sausages. I made a half cup test
  batch of 18 different recipes to see which one we liked. Here is the one we
  liked the best. I made a 6# batch and formed it into patties and froze
  them. I did not add the water. I am going to try smoking some the next time
  I fire up the NBBD. I used fresh sage and bay from my herb garden.
  
  Recipe by: Jerry Predika "The Sausage Making Cookbook"
  
  Posted to bbq-digest by wight@odc.net on May 29, 1998
 
</step></directions></recipe></recipeml>
